{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Wi7Hdqwo4QM9rsDB8sYc7T","type":"tool_result","content":"   400→\n   401→### 6.2 TB02: DC Sweep (`tb_ota_dc.spice`)\n   402→\n   403→**Purpose:** Measure output swing, input-output transfer characteristic, linearity.\n   404→\n   405→**Method:**\n   406→- Configure OTA in unity-gain feedback (vout connected to vinn)\n   407→- Sweep vinp from 0 to 1.8 V in 1 mV steps\n   408→- Measure vout vs vinp\n   409→\n   410→**Measurements:**\n   411→```spice\n   412→.dc Vinp 0 1.8 0.001\n   413→.meas dc v_out_max MAX v(vout)\n   414→.meas dc v_out_min MIN v(vout)\n   415→.meas dc swing PARAM='v_out_max - v_out_min'\n   416→```\n   417→\n   418→Also measure the derivative d(Vout)/d(Vinp) — it should be ~1.0 in the linear\n   419→region. The range where it stays within 1% of 1.0 defines the input CM range.\n   420→\n   421→### 6.3 TB03: Transient Step Response (`tb_ota_tran.spice`)\n   422→\n   423→**Purpose:** Measure slew rate, settling time to 0.1%.\n   424→\n   425→**Method:**\n   426→- Configure OTA in unity-gain feedback\n   427→- Apply a 100 mV step at t=10us on the positive input\n   428→- Simulate for 100 us with max timestep of 10 ns\n   429→\n   430→**Measurements:**\n   431→```spice\n   432→.tran 10n 100u\n   433→.meas tran sr_pos DERIV v(vout) WHEN v(vout)='0.9+0.045' RISE=1\n   434→.meas tran sr_neg DERIV v(vout) WHEN v(vout)='0.9+0.045' FALL=1\n   435→.meas tran t_settle_01 WHEN v(vout)='0.9+0.0999' RISE=1\n   436→```\n   437→\n   438→Slew rate should be > 10 mV/us. For 500 nA tail current and 10 pF load:\n   439→SR = Itail / CL = 500n / 10p = 50 mV/us (theoretical). Should be close.\n   440→\n   441→### 6.4 TB04: Noise Analysis (`tb_ota_noise.spice`)\n   442→\n   443→**Purpose:** Measure input-referred noise spectral density and integrated noise.\n   444→\n   445→**Method:**\n   446→- Same bias as AC testbench\n   447→- Run: `.noise V(vout) Vinp dec 100 1 1Meg`\n   448→- The result is output-referred; divide by gain to get input-referred,\n   449→  or use ngspice's built-in input-referred noise output\n   450→\n   451→**Measurements:**\n   452→```spice\n   453→.noise V(vout) Vinp dec 100 1 1Meg\n   454→.print noise inoise_spectrum\n   455→.meas noise noise_1k FIND inoise_total AT=1000\n   456→.meas noise noise_10k FIND inoise_total AT=10000\n   457→```\n   458→\n   459→**Expected:** At 1 kHz, dominated by 1/f noise of input pair. With W*L = 10 um^2,\n   460→the 1/f noise coefficient Kf for sky130 NMOS gives roughly 100-180 nV/rtHz.\n   461→At 10 kHz, thermal noise dominates: Sn = (8/3)*kT/gm * (1 + gm3/gm1) where\n   462→gm3/gm1 is the fold transistor contribution. With gm1 ~ 5 uA/V, thermal floor\n   463→is ~ 40-80 nV/rtHz.\n   464→\n   465→### 6.5 TB05: PSRR (`tb_ota_psrr.spice`)\n   466→\n   467→**Purpose:** Measure power supply rejection ratio.\n   468→\n   469→**Method:**\n   470→- Ground both inputs at Vcm = 0.9 V (no differential input)\n   471→- Apply AC stimulus of 1 V on VDD\n   472→- Measure AC output voltage\n   473→- PSRR = 20*log10(Av_from_vdd / Av_from_input) or equivalently measure the\n   474→  gain from VDD to output and subtract from the open-loop gain\n   475→\n   476→**Measurements:**\n   477→```spice\n   478→.ac dec 100 1 100Meg\n   479→.meas ac psrr_dc FIND vdb(vout) AT=1\n   480→.meas ac psrr_1k FIND vdb(vout) AT=1000\n   481→```\n   482→\n   483→Negate and add DC gain to get PSRR in dB. Target: > 50 dB at 1 kHz.\n   484→\n   485→### 6.6 TB06: CMRR (`tb_ota_cmrr.spice`)\n   486→\n   487→**Purpose:** Measure common-mode rejection ratio.\n   488→\n   489→**Method:**\n   490→- Tie both inputs together\n   491→- Apply AC stimulus of 1 V on the common input\n   492→- Measure AC output voltage\n   493→- CMRR = Adm / Acm (open-loop differential gain / common-mode gain)\n   494→\n   495→**Measurements:**\n   496→```spice\n   497→.ac dec 100 1 100Meg\n   498→.meas ac acm_dc FIND vdb(vout) AT=1\n   499→.meas ac cmrr_dc PARAM='gain_db - acm_dc'\n   500→```\n   501→\n   502→Target: > 60 dB at DC. Limited by tail current source output impedance and\n   503→matching (in simulation with ideal matching, CMRR will appear very high;\n   504→Monte Carlo gives realistic values).\n   505→\n   506→### 6.7 TB07: Operating Point Verification (`tb_ota_op.spice`)\n   507→\n   508→**Purpose:** Print Vgs, Vth, Vds, Id, gm, gds, and operating region for ALL\n   509→13 transistors. This is the most important testbench — it catches 90% of\n   510→design errors.\n   511→\n   512→**Method:**\n   513→```spice\n   514→.op\n   515→.save all\n   516→.control\n   517→  run\n   518→  print @m.xota.m1[vgs] @m.xota.m1[vth] @m.xota.m1[vds]\n   519→  print @m.xota.m1[id] @m.xota.m1[gm] @m.xota.m1[gds]\n   520→  print @m.xota.m1[vdsat] @m.xota.m1[region]\n   521→  * ... repeat for all 13 transistors ...\n   522→  quit\n   523→.endc\n   524→```\n   525→\n   526→**Verification rules (MANDATORY — no exceptions):**\n   527→\n   528→| Check | Condition | Why |\n   529→|-------|-----------|-----|\n   530→| PMOS saturation | Vsg - abs(Vth) > 150 mV | Sky130 PMOS models unreliable below this |\n   531→| NMOS signal path saturation | Vgs - Vth > 50 mV | Need some inversion for gm |\n   532→| Cascode headroom | Vds > Vdsat + 50 mV | Ensure saturation with margin |\n   533→| Tail current accuracy | abs(Id_M11 - 500nA) < 50nA | Bias is correct |\n   534→| Current balance | abs(Id_M1 - Id_M2) < 10nA | Matched at operating point |\n   535→| Output voltage | 0.6V < Vout < 1.2V | Roughly mid-rail |\n   536→\n   537→If ANY of these checks fail, the agent MUST resize the offending transistor(s)\n   538→and re-simulate. Do not proceed to other testbenches until the operating point\n   539→is clean.\n   540→\n   541→### 6.8 TB08: 5-Corner Sweep (`tb_ota_corners.spice`)\n   542→\n   543→**Purpose:** Verify AC specs across all process corners.\n   544→\n   545→**Method:**\n   546→Run tb_ota_ac at each of: TT, SS, FF, SF, FS.\n   547→\n   548→```spice\n   549→.lib \"/path/to/sky130A/libs.tech/ngspice/sky130.lib.spice\" tt\n   550→* ... run AC sim, measure gain/UGB/PM ...\n   551→* Then repeat with ss, ff, sf, fs\n   552→```\n   553→\n   554→In ngspice this is best done with a shell script that swaps the .lib line and\n   555→reruns, or using `.alter` blocks if supported.\n   556→\n   557→**Expected behavior across corners:**\n   558→\n   559→| Corner | Gain change | UGB change | PM change |\n   560→|--------|-------------|------------|-----------|\n   561→| SS | -5 to -8 dB | -30 to -40% | +5 to +10 deg |\n   562→| FF | +3 to +5 dB | +20 to +30% | -5 to -10 deg |\n   563→| SF | -2 to +2 dB | -10 to +10% | -3 to +3 deg |\n   564→| FS | -2 to +2 dB | -10 to +10% | -3 to +3 deg |\n   565→\n   566→The critical corner is SS: gain drops and UGB drops. If gain at SS < 60 dB,\n   567→increase L of cascode devices. If UGB at SS < 30 kHz, increase input pair W\n   568→or increase bias current (with permission from power budget).\n   569→\n   570→### 6.9 TB09: Temperature Sweep (`tb_ota_corners_temp.spice`)\n   571→\n   572→**Purpose:** Verify performance at -40C, 27C, and 85C.\n   573→\n   574→**Method:**\n   575→Run tb_ota_ac at TT corner with `.temp -40`, `.temp 27`, `.temp 85`.\n   576→\n   577→**Expected:**\n   578→- At -40C: threshold voltages increase, mobility increases. Gain may increase\n   579→  slightly, UGB may decrease slightly. Watch for tail current accuracy (if\n   580→  biased by mirror, the reference current tracks temperature).\n   581→- At 85C: thresholds decrease, mobility decreases. gm/Id increases but gm\n   582→  may decrease due to lower mobility. UGB and gain can go either way depending\n   583→  on the bias scheme.\n   584→\n   585→**PASS criteria:** Gain >= 55 dB and UGB in 20-200 kHz at all three temperatures.\n   586→\n   587→### 6.10 TB10: Monte Carlo (`tb_ota_mc.spice`)\n   588→\n   589→**Purpose:** Measure statistical distribution of input offset voltage.\n   590→\n   591→**Method:**\n   592→- Configure OTA in unity-gain feedback with Vinp = 0.9 V\n   593→- Run 200 Monte Carlo iterations with mismatch parameters enabled\n   594→- Measure Vout - 0.9 V for each iteration (this is the input offset)\n   595→\n   596→```spice\n   597→.param mc_run = 0\n   598→.control\n   599→  let offset = vector(200)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"37d800be-0a8d-4fa4-9160-013da436175b","uuid":"2c375c1c-e7eb-4c9c-8d97-5e06db3b21d9","timestamp":"2026-03-22T23:30:16.855Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/ubuntu/analog-ai-chips/vibrosense/01_ota/program.md","content":"\n### 6.2 TB02: DC Sweep (`tb_ota_dc.spice`)\n\n**Purpose:** Measure output swing, input-output transfer characteristic, linearity.\n\n**Method:**\n- Configure OTA in unity-gain feedback (vout connected to vinn)\n- Sweep vinp from 0 to 1.8 V in 1 mV steps\n- Measure vout vs vinp\n\n**Measurements:**\n```spice\n.dc Vinp 0 1.8 0.001\n.meas dc v_out_max MAX v(vout)\n.meas dc v_out_min MIN v(vout)\n.meas dc swing PARAM='v_out_max - v_out_min'\n```\n\nAlso measure the derivative d(Vout)/d(Vinp) — it should be ~1.0 in the linear\nregion. The range where it stays within 1% of 1.0 defines the input CM range.\n\n### 6.3 TB03: Transient Step Response (`tb_ota_tran.spice`)\n\n**Purpose:** Measure slew rate, settling time to 0.1%.\n\n**Method:**\n- Configure OTA in unity-gain feedback\n- Apply a 100 mV step at t=10us on the positive input\n- Simulate for 100 us with max timestep of 10 ns\n\n**Measurements:**\n```spice\n.tran 10n 100u\n.meas tran sr_pos DERIV v(vout) WHEN v(vout)='0.9+0.045' RISE=1\n.meas tran sr_neg DERIV v(vout) WHEN v(vout)='0.9+0.045' FALL=1\n.meas tran t_settle_01 WHEN v(vout)='0.9+0.0999' RISE=1\n```\n\nSlew rate should be > 10 mV/us. For 500 nA tail current and 10 pF load:\nSR = Itail / CL = 500n / 10p = 50 mV/us (theoretical). Should be close.\n\n### 6.4 TB04: Noise Analysis (`tb_ota_noise.spice`)\n\n**Purpose:** Measure input-referred noise spectral density and integrated noise.\n\n**Method:**\n- Same bias as AC testbench\n- Run: `.noise V(vout) Vinp dec 100 1 1Meg`\n- The result is output-referred; divide by gain to get input-referred,\n  or use ngspice's built-in input-referred noise output\n\n**Measurements:**\n```spice\n.noise V(vout) Vinp dec 100 1 1Meg\n.print noise inoise_spectrum\n.meas noise noise_1k FIND inoise_total AT=1000\n.meas noise noise_10k FIND inoise_total AT=10000\n```\n\n**Expected:** At 1 kHz, dominated by 1/f noise of input pair. With W*L = 10 um^2,\nthe 1/f noise coefficient Kf for sky130 NMOS gives roughly 100-180 nV/rtHz.\nAt 10 kHz, thermal noise dominates: Sn = (8/3)*kT/gm * (1 + gm3/gm1) where\ngm3/gm1 is the fold transistor contribution. With gm1 ~ 5 uA/V, thermal floor\nis ~ 40-80 nV/rtHz.\n\n### 6.5 TB05: PSRR (`tb_ota_psrr.spice`)\n\n**Purpose:** Measure power supply rejection ratio.\n\n**Method:**\n- Ground both inputs at Vcm = 0.9 V (no differential input)\n- Apply AC stimulus of 1 V on VDD\n- Measure AC output voltage\n- PSRR = 20*log10(Av_from_vdd / Av_from_input) or equivalently measure the\n  gain from VDD to output and subtract from the open-loop gain\n\n**Measurements:**\n```spice\n.ac dec 100 1 100Meg\n.meas ac psrr_dc FIND vdb(vout) AT=1\n.meas ac psrr_1k FIND vdb(vout) AT=1000\n```\n\nNegate and add DC gain to get PSRR in dB. Target: > 50 dB at 1 kHz.\n\n### 6.6 TB06: CMRR (`tb_ota_cmrr.spice`)\n\n**Purpose:** Measure common-mode rejection ratio.\n\n**Method:**\n- Tie both inputs together\n- Apply AC stimulus of 1 V on the common input\n- Measure AC output voltage\n- CMRR = Adm / Acm (open-loop differential gain / common-mode gain)\n\n**Measurements:**\n```spice\n.ac dec 100 1 100Meg\n.meas ac acm_dc FIND vdb(vout) AT=1\n.meas ac cmrr_dc PARAM='gain_db - acm_dc'\n```\n\nTarget: > 60 dB at DC. Limited by tail current source output impedance and\nmatching (in simulation with ideal matching, CMRR will appear very high;\nMonte Carlo gives realistic values).\n\n### 6.7 TB07: Operating Point Verification (`tb_ota_op.spice`)\n\n**Purpose:** Print Vgs, Vth, Vds, Id, gm, gds, and operating region for ALL\n13 transistors. This is the most important testbench — it catches 90% of\ndesign errors.\n\n**Method:**\n```spice\n.op\n.save all\n.control\n  run\n  print @m.xota.m1[vgs] @m.xota.m1[vth] @m.xota.m1[vds]\n  print @m.xota.m1[id] @m.xota.m1[gm] @m.xota.m1[gds]\n  print @m.xota.m1[vdsat] @m.xota.m1[region]\n  * ... repeat for all 13 transistors ...\n  quit\n.endc\n```\n\n**Verification rules (MANDATORY — no exceptions):**\n\n| Check | Condition | Why |\n|-------|-----------|-----|\n| PMOS saturation | Vsg - abs(Vth) > 150 mV | Sky130 PMOS models unreliable below this |\n| NMOS signal path saturation | Vgs - Vth > 50 mV | Need some inversion for gm |\n| Cascode headroom | Vds > Vdsat + 50 mV | Ensure saturation with margin |\n| Tail current accuracy | abs(Id_M11 - 500nA) < 50nA | Bias is correct |\n| Current balance | abs(Id_M1 - Id_M2) < 10nA | Matched at operating point |\n| Output voltage | 0.6V < Vout < 1.2V | Roughly mid-rail |\n\nIf ANY of these checks fail, the agent MUST resize the offending transistor(s)\nand re-simulate. Do not proceed to other testbenches until the operating point\nis clean.\n\n### 6.8 TB08: 5-Corner Sweep (`tb_ota_corners.spice`)\n\n**Purpose:** Verify AC specs across all process corners.\n\n**Method:**\nRun tb_ota_ac at each of: TT, SS, FF, SF, FS.\n\n```spice\n.lib \"/path/to/sky130A/libs.tech/ngspice/sky130.lib.spice\" tt\n* ... run AC sim, measure gain/UGB/PM ...\n* Then repeat with ss, ff, sf, fs\n```\n\nIn ngspice this is best done with a shell script that swaps the .lib line and\nreruns, or using `.alter` blocks if supported.\n\n**Expected behavior across corners:**\n\n| Corner | Gain change | UGB change | PM change |\n|--------|-------------|------------|-----------|\n| SS | -5 to -8 dB | -30 to -40% | +5 to +10 deg |\n| FF | +3 to +5 dB | +20 to +30% | -5 to -10 deg |\n| SF | -2 to +2 dB | -10 to +10% | -3 to +3 deg |\n| FS | -2 to +2 dB | -10 to +10% | -3 to +3 deg |\n\nThe critical corner is SS: gain drops and UGB drops. If gain at SS < 60 dB,\nincrease L of cascode devices. If UGB at SS < 30 kHz, increase input pair W\nor increase bias current (with permission from power budget).\n\n### 6.9 TB09: Temperature Sweep (`tb_ota_corners_temp.spice`)\n\n**Purpose:** Verify performance at -40C, 27C, and 85C.\n\n**Method:**\nRun tb_ota_ac at TT corner with `.temp -40`, `.temp 27`, `.temp 85`.\n\n**Expected:**\n- At -40C: threshold voltages increase, mobility increases. Gain may increase\n  slightly, UGB may decrease slightly. Watch for tail current accuracy (if\n  biased by mirror, the reference current tracks temperature).\n- At 85C: thresholds decrease, mobility decreases. gm/Id increases but gm\n  may decrease due to lower mobility. UGB and gain can go either way depending\n  on the bias scheme.\n\n**PASS criteria:** Gain >= 55 dB and UGB in 20-200 kHz at all three temperatures.\n\n### 6.10 TB10: Monte Carlo (`tb_ota_mc.spice`)\n\n**Purpose:** Measure statistical distribution of input offset voltage.\n\n**Method:**\n- Configure OTA in unity-gain feedback with Vinp = 0.9 V\n- Run 200 Monte Carlo iterations with mismatch parameters enabled\n- Measure Vout - 0.9 V for each iteration (this is the input offset)\n\n```spice\n.param mc_run = 0\n.control\n  let offset = vector(200)","numLines":200,"startLine":400,"totalLines":974}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01AcjkEPTtT3Vc8Dspqg2k28","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01DqtNR1aeUUt7r77xptcqEx","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/analog-ai-chips/vibrosense/01_ota/program.md","offset":600,"limit":200},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3272,"cache_read_input_tokens":36817,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3272},"output_tokens":70,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"37d800be-0a8d-4fa4-9160-013da436175b","uuid":"2a0fe562-eb99-49e8-94b7-d2b61e781c81"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DqtNR1aeUUt7r77xptcqEx","type":"tool_result","content":"   600→  let idx = 0\n   601→  repeat 200\n   602→    set mc_run = $&idx\n   603→    reset\n   604→    run\n   605→    let offset[idx] = v(vout) - 0.9\n   606→    let idx = idx + 1\n   607→  end\n   608→  print mean(offset) stddev(offset)\n   609→  * 3-sigma should be < 10 mV\n   610→.endc\n   611→```\n   612→\n   613→Note: SKY130 Monte Carlo models include both inter-die (global) and intra-die\n   614→(mismatch) variations. The mismatch parameters are in the model files as\n   615→`delvto` and similar. Verify that the `.lib` call includes the MC models.\n   616→\n   617→**PASS criteria:** 3-sigma offset < 10 mV. If offset is too high, increase\n   618→the area (W*L) of the input pair. Offset scales as 1/sqrt(W*L) — doubling\n   619→the area reduces offset by ~1.4x.\n   620→\n   621→---\n   622→\n   623→## 7. Operating Point Verification — The Cardinal Rule\n   624→\n   625→This section exists because operating point errors are the #1 cause of analog\n   626→simulation mismatch with silicon. The agent MUST follow this procedure after\n   627→every simulation change.\n   628→\n   629→### 7.1 Procedure\n   630→\n   631→1. Run `.op` simulation\n   632→2. For each of the 13 transistors, extract: Vgs, Vth, Vds, Vdsat, Id, gm, gds, region\n   633→3. Compute Vov = Vgs - Vth (NMOS) or Vsg - |Vth| (PMOS)\n   634→4. Check ALL of the following:\n   635→\n   636→**For PMOS devices (M3, M4, M5, M6, M12, M13):**\n   637→- Region must be \"saturation\" (region = 2 in ngspice)\n   638→- Vov = Vsg - |Vth| must be > 150 mV\n   639→- If Vov < 150 mV, the BSIM model for sky130 PMOS may give unreliable gm and\n   640→  gds. Increase W to push the device further into moderate/strong inversion,\n   641→  or increase the bias current through the device.\n   642→\n   643→**For signal-path NMOS devices (M1, M2, M7, M8):**\n   644→- Region must be \"saturation\" (region = 2)\n   645→- Vov = Vgs - Vth must be > 50 mV\n   646→- M1/M2 can operate in weak-to-moderate inversion (Vov ~ 50-100 mV) for\n   647→  maximum gm/Id ratio, but going below 50 mV risks model inaccuracy\n   648→\n   649→**For current-source NMOS devices (M9, M10, M11):**\n   650→- Region must be \"saturation\" (region = 2)\n   651→- Vds > Vdsat + 50 mV (headroom for keeping saturation across corners)\n   652→- These devices can operate anywhere from weak to strong inversion; the key\n   653→  constraint is saturation headroom, not Vov\n   654→\n   655→**For all cascode devices (M5, M6, M7, M8):**\n   656→- Vds > Vdsat + 50 mV (absolute minimum)\n   657→- Preferably Vds > Vdsat + 100 mV for margin across corners\n   658→- If this is not met, the cascode device provides no impedance boost and the\n   659→  gain drops precipitously\n   660→\n   661→### 7.2 What to Do When a Device Violates\n   662→\n   663→| Violation | Root cause | Fix |\n   664→|-----------|-----------|-----|\n   665→| PMOS Vov < 150 mV | Device too wide for its current, or current too low | Decrease W or increase L to push Vgs higher |\n   666→| NMOS Vov < 50 mV | Device in deep subthreshold | Decrease W or increase current |\n   667→| Cascode Vds < Vdsat + 50 mV | Stacking too many devices, not enough voltage headroom | Decrease L of cascode device (reduces Vdsat) or adjust bias voltages |\n   668→| Device in triode (region = 1) | Vds too low, likely a biasing error | Check bias voltage generation, may need to adjust Vbcn or Vbcp |\n   669→| Device in cutoff (region = 3) | Vgs < Vth, no current flowing | Check connectivity, bias source, W/L ratio |\n   670→\n   671→### 7.3 Operating Point Reporting Format\n   672→\n   673→After every `.op` run, the agent must produce a table like this:\n   674→\n   675→```\n   676→Device  | Type | W/L     | Id(nA) | Vgs(V) | Vth(V) | Vov(mV) | Vds(V) | Vdsat(V) | gm(uS) | Region | Status\n   677→--------|------|---------|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|----------|---------|--------|-------\n   678→M1      | NMOS | 10/1    | 250    | 0.50   | 0.45   | +50     | 0.65   | 0.08     | 5.0     | Sat    | OK\n   679→M2      | NMOS | 10/1    | 250    | 0.50   | 0.45   | +50     | 0.65   | 0.08     | 5.0     | Sat    | OK\n   680→...\n   681→```\n   682→\n   683→Every row must end with OK or FAIL. If any row is FAIL, do not proceed.\n   684→\n   685→---\n   686→\n   687→## 8. Layout Guidelines\n   688→\n   689→### 8.1 Floorplan\n   690→\n   691→```\n   692→+--------------------------------------------------+\n   693→|                  Guard Ring (N+)                   |\n   694→|  +----------------------------------------------+|\n   695→|  |  M12/M13 (PMOS bias)    |  Bias routing      ||\n   696→|  |__________________________|____________________||\n   697→|  |                                                ||\n   698→|  |     M3  M5  |  M6  M4    <- PMOS loads        ||\n   699→|  |     (cascode + fold)     |  matched pair       ||\n   700→|  |______________________________ _________________||\n   701→|  |                                                ||\n   702→|  |        M1   M2           <- Input pair         ||\n   703→|  |      (ABBA centroid)     |  CRITICAL match     ||\n   704→|  |______________________________ _________________||\n   705→|  |                                                ||\n   706→|  |     M9  M7  |  M8  M10   <- NMOS loads        ||\n   707→|  |     (cascode + current)  |  matched pair       ||\n   708→|  |______________________________ _________________||\n   709→|  |                                                ||\n   710→|  |          M11              <- Tail current      ||\n   711→|  |      (isolated)          |                     ||\n   712→|  +----------------------------------------------+|\n   713→|                  Guard Ring (P+)                   |\n   714→+--------------------------------------------------+\n   715→```\n   716→\n   717→### 8.2 Input Pair Matching (M1/M2) — CRITICAL\n   718→\n   719→The input pair M1/M2 determines offset and CMRR. Layout rules:\n   720→\n   721→1. **Common centroid, ABBA interleaving:** Place M1 and M2 fingers as\n   722→   A-B-B-A, where A = M1 finger and B = M2 finger. With 2 fingers each,\n   723→   this gives exactly the 4-finger ABBA pattern.\n   724→2. **Identical orientation:** Both transistors must have the same gate\n   725→   orientation (e.g., both with gates running vertically).\n   726→3. **Dummy devices:** Place dummy transistors on both ends of the array to\n   727→   shield the active devices from edge effects (etch non-uniformity at the\n   728→   array boundary).\n   729→4. **Shared source:** The source connections of M1 and M2 connect to M11's\n   730→   drain — route this as a symmetric tree from the center.\n   731→5. **Minimal drain routing asymmetry:** The drain of M1 goes to the M3/M5\n   732→   branch and the drain of M2 goes to the M4/M6 branch. Route these\n   733→   symmetrically — same metal layer, same wire length, same number of vias.\n   734→\n   735→### 8.3 PMOS Load Matching (M3/M4 and M5/M6)\n   736→\n   737→1. **Common centroid:** M3/M4 as A-B-B-A, M5/M6 as A-B-B-A.\n   738→2. **Same N-well:** All PMOS devices in a single N-well to avoid well\n   739→   potential variations.\n   740→3. **Close to input pair:** Minimize wire length from input pair drains to\n   741→   fold node — parasitic capacitance here degrades phase margin.\n   742→\n   743→### 8.4 NMOS Cascode and Current Sources (M7-M10)\n   744→\n   745→1. **M7/M8 matched:** Common centroid like the input pair.\n   746→2. **M9/M10 matched:** These set the current — matching matters.\n   747→3. **Same P-sub potential:** All NMOS share the P-substrate; use substrate\n   748→   contacts every 15 um to keep the body potential uniform.\n   749→\n   750→### 8.5 Tail Current (M11)\n   751→\n   752→1. **Isolated:** Place M11 away from the signal-path devices. Its switching\n   753→   noise (from common-mode input variations) should not couple into the\n   754→   differential pair.\n   755→2. **Large area:** With W=4u, L=4u, this is a big device. Use multiple\n   756→   fingers if needed for better current distribution.\n   757→\n   758→### 8.6 Guard Rings\n   759→\n   760→1. **Full guard ring around the entire OTA:** N+ ring tied to VDD and P+ ring\n   761→   tied to VSS. This provides latch-up protection and isolates the OTA from\n   762→   substrate noise injected by digital circuits.\n   763→2. **Individual guard rings optional:** Around the input pair for extra\n   764→   isolation (recommended if the OTA will be placed near a switched-capacitor\n   765→   circuit or clock buffer).\n   766→\n   767→### 8.7 Routing Rules\n   768→\n   769→1. **Differential signals:** Route on the same metal layer, same width, same\n   770→   length. If one wire must jog, add a compensating jog to the other.\n   771→2. **Bias lines:** Route on Metal 2 or higher to avoid coupling to Metal 1\n   772→   signal routes.\n   773→3. **VDD/VSS:** Wide traces (minimum 1 um) running horizontally across the\n   774→   top and bottom of the cell. Multiple vias to lower metals at every device\n   775→   connection.\n   776→4. **Output node:** The output is the highest-impedance node. Keep the wire\n   777→   short and shield it with grounded metal on adjacent layers if possible.\n   778→5. **No floating metal:** Every piece of metal must be connected. Floating\n   779→   metal causes antenna rule violations and can couple noise.\n   780→\n   781→---\n   782→\n   783→## 9. Troubleshooting Guide — When Stuck\n   784→\n   785→### 9.1 Gain is Low (< 60 dB)\n   786→\n   787→**Likely causes:**\n   788→1. Cascode devices not providing enough impedance boost — check that M5/M6\n   789→   and M7/M8 are in saturation with adequate Vds headroom.\n   790→2. Cascode L is too short — gm*ro of the cascode is proportional to L.\n   791→   Try increasing L of M5/M6 from 0.5u to 1u or M7/M8 from 0.5u to 1u.\n   792→3. Output resistance of M9/M10 is too low — increase L of M9/M10 from 2u\n   793→   to 4u.\n   794→4. Device is accidentally in triode — run `.op` and check region flags.\n   795→\n   796→**Systematic approach:**\n   797→- Compute Rout = (gm5 * ro5 * ro3) || (gm7 * ro7 * ro9)\n   798→- Av = gm1 * Rout\n   799→- Identify which side (PMOS or NMOS) has lower impedance and fix that one."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"37d800be-0a8d-4fa4-9160-013da436175b","uuid":"05ce37bf-5496-4f2e-bdd6-7215a13d00b8","timestamp":"2026-03-22T23:30:19.722Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/ubuntu/analog-ai-chips/vibrosense/01_ota/program.md","content":"  let idx = 0\n  repeat 200\n    set mc_run = $&idx\n    reset\n    run\n    let offset[idx] = v(vout) - 0.9\n    let idx = idx + 1\n  end\n  print mean(offset) stddev(offset)\n  * 3-sigma should be < 10 mV\n.endc\n```\n\nNote: SKY130 Monte Carlo models include both inter-die (global) and intra-die\n(mismatch) variations. The mismatch parameters are in the model files as\n`delvto` and similar. Verify that the `.lib` call includes the MC models.\n\n**PASS criteria:** 3-sigma offset < 10 mV. If offset is too high, increase\nthe area (W*L) of the input pair. Offset scales as 1/sqrt(W*L) — doubling\nthe area reduces offset by ~1.4x.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Operating Point Verification — The Cardinal Rule\n\nThis section exists because operating point errors are the #1 cause of analog\nsimulation mismatch with silicon. The agent MUST follow this procedure after\nevery simulation change.\n\n### 7.1 Procedure\n\n1. Run `.op` simulation\n2. For each of the 13 transistors, extract: Vgs, Vth, Vds, Vdsat, Id, gm, gds, region\n3. Compute Vov = Vgs - Vth (NMOS) or Vsg - |Vth| (PMOS)\n4. Check ALL of the following:\n\n**For PMOS devices (M3, M4, M5, M6, M12, M13):**\n- Region must be \"saturation\" (region = 2 in ngspice)\n- Vov = Vsg - |Vth| must be > 150 mV\n- If Vov < 150 mV, the BSIM model for sky130 PMOS may give unreliable gm and\n  gds. Increase W to push the device further into moderate/strong inversion,\n  or increase the bias current through the device.\n\n**For signal-path NMOS devices (M1, M2, M7, M8):**\n- Region must be \"saturation\" (region = 2)\n- Vov = Vgs - Vth must be > 50 mV\n- M1/M2 can operate in weak-to-moderate inversion (Vov ~ 50-100 mV) for\n  maximum gm/Id ratio, but going below 50 mV risks model inaccuracy\n\n**For current-source NMOS devices (M9, M10, M11):**\n- Region must be \"saturation\" (region = 2)\n- Vds > Vdsat + 50 mV (headroom for keeping saturation across corners)\n- These devices can operate anywhere from weak to strong inversion; the key\n  constraint is saturation headroom, not Vov\n\n**For all cascode devices (M5, M6, M7, M8):**\n- Vds > Vdsat + 50 mV (absolute minimum)\n- Preferably Vds > Vdsat + 100 mV for margin across corners\n- If this is not met, the cascode device provides no impedance boost and the\n  gain drops precipitously\n\n### 7.2 What to Do When a Device Violates\n\n| Violation | Root cause | Fix |\n|-----------|-----------|-----|\n| PMOS Vov < 150 mV | Device too wide for its current, or current too low | Decrease W or increase L to push Vgs higher |\n| NMOS Vov < 50 mV | Device in deep subthreshold | Decrease W or increase current |\n| Cascode Vds < Vdsat + 50 mV | Stacking too many devices, not enough voltage headroom | Decrease L of cascode device (reduces Vdsat) or adjust bias voltages |\n| Device in triode (region = 1) | Vds too low, likely a biasing error | Check bias voltage generation, may need to adjust Vbcn or Vbcp |\n| Device in cutoff (region = 3) | Vgs < Vth, no current flowing | Check connectivity, bias source, W/L ratio |\n\n### 7.3 Operating Point Reporting Format\n\nAfter every `.op` run, the agent must produce a table like this:\n\n```\nDevice  | Type | W/L     | Id(nA) | Vgs(V) | Vth(V) | Vov(mV) | Vds(V) | Vdsat(V) | gm(uS) | Region | Status\n--------|------|---------|--------|--------|--------|---------|--------|----------|---------|--------|-------\nM1      | NMOS | 10/1    | 250    | 0.50   | 0.45   | +50     | 0.65   | 0.08     | 5.0     | Sat    | OK\nM2      | NMOS | 10/1    | 250    | 0.50   | 0.45   | +50     | 0.65   | 0.08     | 5.0     | Sat    | OK\n...\n```\n\nEvery row must end with OK or FAIL. If any row is FAIL, do not proceed.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Layout Guidelines\n\n### 8.1 Floorplan\n\n```\n+--------------------------------------------------+\n|                  Guard Ring (N+)                   |\n|  +----------------------------------------------+|\n|  |  M12/M13 (PMOS bias)    |  Bias routing      ||\n|  |__________________________|____________________||\n|  |                                                ||\n|  |     M3  M5  |  M6  M4    <- PMOS loads        ||\n|  |     (cascode + fold)     |  matched pair       ||\n|  |______________________________ _________________||\n|  |                                                ||\n|  |        M1   M2           <- Input pair         ||\n|  |      (ABBA centroid)     |  CRITICAL match     ||\n|  |______________________________ _________________||\n|  |                                                ||\n|  |     M9  M7  |  M8  M10   <- NMOS loads        ||\n|  |     (cascode + current)  |  matched pair       ||\n|  |______________________________ _________________||\n|  |                                                ||\n|  |          M11              <- Tail current      ||\n|  |      (isolated)          |                     ||\n|  +----------------------------------------------+|\n|                  Guard Ring (P+)                   |\n+--------------------------------------------------+\n```\n\n### 8.2 Input Pair Matching (M1/M2) — CRITICAL\n\nThe input pair M1/M2 determines offset and CMRR. Layout rules:\n\n1. **Common centroid, ABBA interleaving:** Place M1 and M2 fingers as\n   A-B-B-A, where A = M1 finger and B = M2 finger. With 2 fingers each,\n   this gives exactly the 4-finger ABBA pattern.\n2. **Identical orientation:** Both transistors must have the same gate\n   orientation (e.g., both with gates running vertically).\n3. **Dummy devices:** Place dummy transistors on both ends of the array to\n   shield the active devices from edge effects (etch non-uniformity at the\n   array boundary).\n4. **Shared source:** The source connections of M1 and M2 connect to M11's\n   drain — route this as a symmetric tree from the center.\n5. **Minimal drain routing asymmetry:** The drain of M1 goes to the M3/M5\n   branch and the drain of M2 goes to the M4/M6 branch. Route these\n   symmetrically — same metal layer, same wire length, same number of vias.\n\n### 8.3 PMOS Load Matching (M3/M4 and M5/M6)\n\n1. **Common centroid:** M3/M4 as A-B-B-A, M5/M6 as A-B-B-A.\n2. **Same N-well:** All PMOS devices in a single N-well to avoid well\n   potential variations.\n3. **Close to input pair:** Minimize wire length from input pair drains to\n   fold node — parasitic capacitance here degrades phase margin.\n\n### 8.4 NMOS Cascode and Current Sources (M7-M10)\n\n1. **M7/M8 matched:** Common centroid like the input pair.\n2. **M9/M10 matched:** These set the current — matching matters.\n3. **Same P-sub potential:** All NMOS share the P-substrate; use substrate\n   contacts every 15 um to keep the body potential uniform.\n\n### 8.5 Tail Current (M11)\n\n1. **Isolated:** Place M11 away from the signal-path devices. Its switching\n   noise (from common-mode input variations) should not couple into the\n   differential pair.\n2. **Large area:** With W=4u, L=4u, this is a big device. Use multiple\n   fingers if needed for better current distribution.\n\n### 8.6 Guard Rings\n\n1. **Full guard ring around the entire OTA:** N+ ring tied to VDD and P+ ring\n   tied to VSS. This provides latch-up protection and isolates the OTA from\n   substrate noise injected by digital circuits.\n2. **Individual guard rings optional:** Around the input pair for extra\n   isolation (recommended if the OTA will be placed near a switched-capacitor\n   circuit or clock buffer).\n\n### 8.7 Routing Rules\n\n1. **Differential signals:** Route on the same metal layer, same width, same\n   length. If one wire must jog, add a compensating jog to the other.\n2. **Bias lines:** Route on Metal 2 or higher to avoid coupling to Metal 1\n   signal routes.\n3. **VDD/VSS:** Wide traces (minimum 1 um) running horizontally across the\n   top and bottom of the cell. Multiple vias to lower metals at every device\n   connection.\n4. **Output node:** The output is the highest-impedance node. Keep the wire\n   short and shield it with grounded metal on adjacent layers if possible.\n5. **No floating metal:** Every piece of metal must be connected. Floating\n   metal causes antenna rule violations and can couple noise.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Troubleshooting Guide — When Stuck\n\n### 9.1 Gain is Low (< 60 dB)\n\n**Likely causes:**\n1. Cascode devices not providing enough impedance boost — check that M5/M6\n   and M7/M8 are in saturation with adequate Vds headroom.\n2. Cascode L is too short — gm*ro of the cascode is proportional to L.\n   Try increasing L of M5/M6 from 0.5u to 1u or M7/M8 from 0.5u to 1u.\n3. Output resistance of M9/M10 is too low — increase L of M9/M10 from 2u\n   to 4u.\n4. Device is accidentally in triode — run `.op` and check region flags.\n\n**Systematic approach:**\n- Compute Rout = (gm5 * ro5 * ro3) || (gm7 * ro7 * ro9)\n- Av = gm1 * Rout\n- Identify which side (PMOS or NMOS) has lower impedance and fix that one.","numLines":200,"startLine":600,"totalLines":974}}}
