{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01N4gShmT5vw6S2uyJ4bLrzo","type":"tool_result","content":"   800→\n   801→### 9.2 UGB is Low (< 30 kHz)\n   802→\n   803→**Likely causes:**\n   804→1. Input pair gm is too low — either W is too small or bias current is too low.\n   805→2. Parasitic capacitance at the output node is large (bad layout, long wires).\n   806→3. Load capacitance is larger than expected.\n   807→\n   808→**Fix:** UGB = gm1 / (2*pi*CL). To increase UGB:\n   809→- Increase W of input pair (increases gm at same current)\n   810→- Increase bias current (increases gm, but costs power)\n   811→- Reduce CL if the system allows it\n   812→\n   813→### 9.3 Phase Margin is Low (< 55 deg)\n   814→\n   815→**Likely causes:**\n   816→1. Non-dominant pole is too close to UGB. The non-dominant pole is at the\n   817→   folding nodes: f_p2 ~ gm_cascode / (2*pi*C_fold). Large parasitic\n   818→   capacitance at the fold node pushes p2 down.\n   819→2. A zero from gate-drain capacitance of the cascode devices.\n   820→\n   821→**Fix:**\n   822→- Reduce parasitic at fold nodes: shorter wires, smaller cascode device widths\n   823→- Increase gm of cascode devices: increase their W or current\n   824→- As last resort, add Miller compensation (Cc between output and a\n   825→  low-impedance node), but this converts the design into a quasi-two-stage\n   826→  and reduces slew rate\n   827→\n   828→### 9.4 Noise is Too High\n   829→\n   830→**Likely causes:**\n   831→1. Input pair too small — 1/f noise scales as 1/(W*L*Cox*f). Increase W*L.\n   832→2. PMOS fold transistor noise contribution — gm3/gm1 ratio is too high.\n   833→   Reduce gm3 by making M3/M4 longer (increases Vov, reduces gm at same Id).\n   834→\n   835→**Fix:**\n   836→- Increase W*L of input pair. Going from W=10u L=1u to W=20u L=1u halves\n   837→  the 1/f noise power (reduces noise voltage by 1.4x).\n   838→- Decrease gm of fold transistors: increase their L.\n   839→- Check that the noise simulation is input-referred, not output-referred.\n   840→\n   841→### 9.5 Output Swing is Too Narrow\n   842→\n   843→**Likely causes:**\n   844→1. Cascode stacking consumes too much headroom.\n   845→2. Vdsat of M5/M6 or M7/M8 is too large (devices too narrow or too much current).\n   846→\n   847→**Fix:**\n   848→- Maximum output voltage: VDD - Vdsat_M3 - Vdsat_M5 = 1.8 - 0.15 - 0.10 = 1.55 V\n   849→- Minimum output voltage: Vdsat_M9 + Vdsat_M7 = 0.10 + 0.10 = 0.20 V\n   850→- Theoretical swing: 1.55 - 0.20 = 1.35 V, which is > 1.0 Vpp target.\n   851→- If swing is less, check that Vdsat values are correct. Reduce by making\n   852→  devices wider (spreads current over more W, reducing Vov/Vdsat).\n   853→\n   854→### 9.6 Settling Time is Too Long\n   855→\n   856→**Likely causes:**\n   857→1. Slew rate limited: SR = Itail / CL. With 500nA and 10pF, SR = 50 mV/us.\n   858→   For a 100 mV step, slewing takes ~2 us. Then linear settling takes\n   859→   several time constants tau = CL / gm ~ 10p / 5u = 2 us. Total settling\n   860→   ~ 10-15 us for 0.1%.\n   861→2. If settling is much longer than expected, look for a slow parasitic pole\n   862→   or ringing (low phase margin).\n   863→\n   864→**Fix:**\n   865→- Increase tail current to improve slew rate\n   866→- Improve phase margin to reduce ringing during linear settling\n   867→\n   868→### 9.7 Monte Carlo Offset is Too High\n   869→\n   870→**Likely causes:**\n   871→1. Input pair area too small — offset is proportional to 1/sqrt(W*L).\n   872→2. Threshold voltage mismatch parameter (AVT) for sky130 NMOS is typically\n   873→   ~5 mV*um. For W=10u, L=1u: sigma_Vth = AVT / sqrt(W*L) = 5m/sqrt(10)\n   874→   ~ 1.6 mV per transistor. Differential pair offset sigma = 1.6*sqrt(2) ~\n   875→   2.2 mV. 3-sigma ~ 6.6 mV — within our 10 mV target.\n   876→\n   877→**Fix:** If offset is too high, increase W*L of the input pair. This also\n   878→improves noise, so it is a double win.\n   879→\n   880→---\n   881→\n   882→## 10. Integration Notes\n   883→\n   884→### 10.1 Interface to Block 00 (Bias Generator)\n   885→\n   886→The OTA receives four bias voltages from Block 00:\n   887→- Vbn: gate voltage for NMOS current sources (M9/M10/M11)\n   888→- Vbcn: gate voltage for NMOS cascode (M7/M8)\n   889→- Vbp: gate voltage for PMOS current sources (M3/M4 or M12/M13)\n   890→- Vbcp: gate voltage for PMOS cascode (M5/M6)\n   891→\n   892→For initial development, replace these with ideal voltage sources set to the\n   893→values from the operating point simulation. Once Block 00 is designed, replace\n   894→the ideal sources with the actual bias generator outputs and re-verify all\n   895→specs.\n   896→\n   897→### 10.2 Interface to Block 02+ (Gm-C Filters)\n   898→\n   899→The OTA will be used as a transconductor in Gm-C filter stages. The filter\n   900→uses the OTA's gm to set the frequency: f = gm / (2*pi*C). The OTA must have:\n   901→- Predictable gm (use moderate inversion where gm/Id is well-controlled)\n   902→- Linear gm over the signal swing (key for low distortion)\n   903→- Frequency-independent gm up to 5x the filter cutoff frequency\n   904→\n   905→The Gm-C interface is: Vinp/Vinn are the filter input, and the output current\n   906→(Iout = gm * Vdiff) flows into the integration capacitor. The OTA output\n   907→node connects to the capacitor, and the voltage on that capacitor is the filter\n   908→state variable.\n   909→\n   910→### 10.3 Reusability\n   911→\n   912→This OTA subcircuit must be parameterizable:\n   913→- The bias current can be scaled by changing the mirror ratio in Block 00\n   914→- For higher-bandwidth filters, multiple OTAs can be paralleled (doubling gm)\n   915→- For lower-noise applications, the input pair can be upsized in a variant\n   916→\n   917→The agent should write the subcircuit with `.param` statements for all device\n   918→sizes so that variants can be created by overriding parameters at instantiation.\n   919→\n   920→---\n   921→\n   922→## 11. Checklist Before Declaring Block 01 Complete\n   923→\n   924→```\n   925→[ ] Operating point of all 13 transistors verified (Section 7)\n   926→[ ] AC gain >= 60 dB across all corners\n   927→[ ] UGB in 30-150 kHz across all corners\n   928→[ ] PM >= 55 degrees across all corners\n   929→[ ] Gain margin >= 10 dB\n   930→[ ] Slew rate >= 10 mV/us\n   931→[ ] Input noise at 1 kHz <= 200 nV/rtHz\n   932→[ ] Input noise at 10 kHz <= 100 nV/rtHz\n   933→[ ] CMRR >= 60 dB at DC\n   934→[ ] PSRR >= 50 dB at 1 kHz\n   935→[ ] Output swing >= 1.0 Vpp at 1% THD\n   936→[ ] Total current <= 2 uA\n   937→[ ] Input CM range >= 0.6 V\n   938→[ ] Temperature sweep passes (-40, 27, 85 C)\n   939→[ ] Monte Carlo 200 runs: offset 3-sigma < 10 mV\n   940→[ ] Layout DRC clean\n   941→[ ] LVS clean (Netgen zero mismatches)\n   942→[ ] Post-PEX simulation meets all specs with < 10% degradation\n   943→[ ] results.md written with all numbers and PASS/FAIL flags\n   944→[ ] Subcircuit netlist is clean, commented, and reusable\n   945→```\n   946→\n   947→---\n   948→\n   949→## 12. References\n   950→\n   951→1. K. Bult and G. J. G. M. Geelen, \"A fast-settling CMOS op amp for SC\n   952→   circuits with 90-dB DC gain,\" IEEE JSSC, vol. 25, no. 6, Dec. 1990.\n   953→   (The original folded-cascode paper is Bult & Wallinga, JSSC 1987.)\n   954→2. V. Peluso, P. Vancorenland, A. Marques, M. Steyaert, and W. Sansen,\n   955→   \"A 900-mV low-power delta-sigma A/D converter with 77-dB dynamic range,\"\n   956→   IEEE JSSC, vol. 33, no. 12, Dec. 1998. (Peluso's ultra-low-power OTA\n   957→   work was published in several papers around 1997-1998.)\n   958→3. P. M. Ferreira and S. Pinto, \"A 1-V 120-nW folded-cascode OTA for\n   959→   neural signal acquisition,\" TCAS-I, 2004.\n   960→4. L. H. C. Toledo et al., \"A review of ultra-low-voltage and ultra-low-power\n   961→   OTA topologies for analog signal processing,\" Journal of Integrated\n   962→   Circuits and Systems, 2019.\n   963→5. SkyWater SKY130 PDK documentation: https://skywater-pdk.readthedocs.io/\n   964→6. B. Razavi, \"Design of Analog CMOS Integrated Circuits,\" 2nd ed.,\n   965→   McGraw-Hill, 2017. Chapters 9 (cascode stages) and 10 (differential\n   966→   amplifiers).\n   967→7. P. Allen and D. Holberg, \"CMOS Analog Circuit Design,\" 3rd ed., Oxford\n   968→   University Press, 2012. Chapter 6 (folded-cascode OTA design procedure).\n   969→\n   970→---\n   971→\n   972→*End of Block 01 program. Total estimated design time: 2-4 hours for schematic\n   973→and simulation, 4-8 hours for layout and post-PEX verification.*\n   974→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"37d800be-0a8d-4fa4-9160-013da436175b","uuid":"8f5ddda3-c0e1-4b12-a94a-878d961e7bfb","timestamp":"2026-03-22T23:30:22.085Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/ubuntu/analog-ai-chips/vibrosense/01_ota/program.md","content":"\n### 9.2 UGB is Low (< 30 kHz)\n\n**Likely causes:**\n1. Input pair gm is too low — either W is too small or bias current is too low.\n2. Parasitic capacitance at the output node is large (bad layout, long wires).\n3. Load capacitance is larger than expected.\n\n**Fix:** UGB = gm1 / (2*pi*CL). To increase UGB:\n- Increase W of input pair (increases gm at same current)\n- Increase bias current (increases gm, but costs power)\n- Reduce CL if the system allows it\n\n### 9.3 Phase Margin is Low (< 55 deg)\n\n**Likely causes:**\n1. Non-dominant pole is too close to UGB. The non-dominant pole is at the\n   folding nodes: f_p2 ~ gm_cascode / (2*pi*C_fold). Large parasitic\n   capacitance at the fold node pushes p2 down.\n2. A zero from gate-drain capacitance of the cascode devices.\n\n**Fix:**\n- Reduce parasitic at fold nodes: shorter wires, smaller cascode device widths\n- Increase gm of cascode devices: increase their W or current\n- As last resort, add Miller compensation (Cc between output and a\n  low-impedance node), but this converts the design into a quasi-two-stage\n  and reduces slew rate\n\n### 9.4 Noise is Too High\n\n**Likely causes:**\n1. Input pair too small — 1/f noise scales as 1/(W*L*Cox*f). Increase W*L.\n2. PMOS fold transistor noise contribution — gm3/gm1 ratio is too high.\n   Reduce gm3 by making M3/M4 longer (increases Vov, reduces gm at same Id).\n\n**Fix:**\n- Increase W*L of input pair. Going from W=10u L=1u to W=20u L=1u halves\n  the 1/f noise power (reduces noise voltage by 1.4x).\n- Decrease gm of fold transistors: increase their L.\n- Check that the noise simulation is input-referred, not output-referred.\n\n### 9.5 Output Swing is Too Narrow\n\n**Likely causes:**\n1. Cascode stacking consumes too much headroom.\n2. Vdsat of M5/M6 or M7/M8 is too large (devices too narrow or too much current).\n\n**Fix:**\n- Maximum output voltage: VDD - Vdsat_M3 - Vdsat_M5 = 1.8 - 0.15 - 0.10 = 1.55 V\n- Minimum output voltage: Vdsat_M9 + Vdsat_M7 = 0.10 + 0.10 = 0.20 V\n- Theoretical swing: 1.55 - 0.20 = 1.35 V, which is > 1.0 Vpp target.\n- If swing is less, check that Vdsat values are correct. Reduce by making\n  devices wider (spreads current over more W, reducing Vov/Vdsat).\n\n### 9.6 Settling Time is Too Long\n\n**Likely causes:**\n1. Slew rate limited: SR = Itail / CL. With 500nA and 10pF, SR = 50 mV/us.\n   For a 100 mV step, slewing takes ~2 us. Then linear settling takes\n   several time constants tau = CL / gm ~ 10p / 5u = 2 us. Total settling\n   ~ 10-15 us for 0.1%.\n2. If settling is much longer than expected, look for a slow parasitic pole\n   or ringing (low phase margin).\n\n**Fix:**\n- Increase tail current to improve slew rate\n- Improve phase margin to reduce ringing during linear settling\n\n### 9.7 Monte Carlo Offset is Too High\n\n**Likely causes:**\n1. Input pair area too small — offset is proportional to 1/sqrt(W*L).\n2. Threshold voltage mismatch parameter (AVT) for sky130 NMOS is typically\n   ~5 mV*um. For W=10u, L=1u: sigma_Vth = AVT / sqrt(W*L) = 5m/sqrt(10)\n   ~ 1.6 mV per transistor. Differential pair offset sigma = 1.6*sqrt(2) ~\n   2.2 mV. 3-sigma ~ 6.6 mV — within our 10 mV target.\n\n**Fix:** If offset is too high, increase W*L of the input pair. This also\nimproves noise, so it is a double win.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Integration Notes\n\n### 10.1 Interface to Block 00 (Bias Generator)\n\nThe OTA receives four bias voltages from Block 00:\n- Vbn: gate voltage for NMOS current sources (M9/M10/M11)\n- Vbcn: gate voltage for NMOS cascode (M7/M8)\n- Vbp: gate voltage for PMOS current sources (M3/M4 or M12/M13)\n- Vbcp: gate voltage for PMOS cascode (M5/M6)\n\nFor initial development, replace these with ideal voltage sources set to the\nvalues from the operating point simulation. Once Block 00 is designed, replace\nthe ideal sources with the actual bias generator outputs and re-verify all\nspecs.\n\n### 10.2 Interface to Block 02+ (Gm-C Filters)\n\nThe OTA will be used as a transconductor in Gm-C filter stages. The filter\nuses the OTA's gm to set the frequency: f = gm / (2*pi*C). The OTA must have:\n- Predictable gm (use moderate inversion where gm/Id is well-controlled)\n- Linear gm over the signal swing (key for low distortion)\n- Frequency-independent gm up to 5x the filter cutoff frequency\n\nThe Gm-C interface is: Vinp/Vinn are the filter input, and the output current\n(Iout = gm * Vdiff) flows into the integration capacitor. The OTA output\nnode connects to the capacitor, and the voltage on that capacitor is the filter\nstate variable.\n\n### 10.3 Reusability\n\nThis OTA subcircuit must be parameterizable:\n- The bias current can be scaled by changing the mirror ratio in Block 00\n- For higher-bandwidth filters, multiple OTAs can be paralleled (doubling gm)\n- For lower-noise applications, the input pair can be upsized in a variant\n\nThe agent should write the subcircuit with `.param` statements for all device\nsizes so that variants can be created by overriding parameters at instantiation.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Checklist Before Declaring Block 01 Complete\n\n```\n[ ] Operating point of all 13 transistors verified (Section 7)\n[ ] AC gain >= 60 dB across all corners\n[ ] UGB in 30-150 kHz across all corners\n[ ] PM >= 55 degrees across all corners\n[ ] Gain margin >= 10 dB\n[ ] Slew rate >= 10 mV/us\n[ ] Input noise at 1 kHz <= 200 nV/rtHz\n[ ] Input noise at 10 kHz <= 100 nV/rtHz\n[ ] CMRR >= 60 dB at DC\n[ ] PSRR >= 50 dB at 1 kHz\n[ ] Output swing >= 1.0 Vpp at 1% THD\n[ ] Total current <= 2 uA\n[ ] Input CM range >= 0.6 V\n[ ] Temperature sweep passes (-40, 27, 85 C)\n[ ] Monte Carlo 200 runs: offset 3-sigma < 10 mV\n[ ] Layout DRC clean\n[ ] LVS clean (Netgen zero mismatches)\n[ ] Post-PEX simulation meets all specs with < 10% degradation\n[ ] results.md written with all numbers and PASS/FAIL flags\n[ ] Subcircuit netlist is clean, commented, and reusable\n```\n\n---\n\n## 12. References\n\n1. K. Bult and G. J. G. M. Geelen, \"A fast-settling CMOS op amp for SC\n   circuits with 90-dB DC gain,\" IEEE JSSC, vol. 25, no. 6, Dec. 1990.\n   (The original folded-cascode paper is Bult & Wallinga, JSSC 1987.)\n2. V. Peluso, P. Vancorenland, A. Marques, M. Steyaert, and W. Sansen,\n   \"A 900-mV low-power delta-sigma A/D converter with 77-dB dynamic range,\"\n   IEEE JSSC, vol. 33, no. 12, Dec. 1998. (Peluso's ultra-low-power OTA\n   work was published in several papers around 1997-1998.)\n3. P. M. Ferreira and S. Pinto, \"A 1-V 120-nW folded-cascode OTA for\n   neural signal acquisition,\" TCAS-I, 2004.\n4. L. H. C. Toledo et al., \"A review of ultra-low-voltage and ultra-low-power\n   OTA topologies for analog signal processing,\" Journal of Integrated\n   Circuits and Systems, 2019.\n5. SkyWater SKY130 PDK documentation: https://skywater-pdk.readthedocs.io/\n6. B. Razavi, \"Design of Analog CMOS Integrated Circuits,\" 2nd ed.,\n   McGraw-Hill, 2017. Chapters 9 (cascode stages) and 10 (differential\n   amplifiers).\n7. P. Allen and D. Holberg, \"CMOS Analog Circuit Design,\" 3rd ed., Oxford\n   University Press, 2012. Chapter 6 (folded-cascode OTA design procedure).\n\n---\n\n*End of Block 01 program. Total estimated design time: 2-4 hours for schematic\nand simulation, 4-8 hours for layout and post-PEX verification.*\n","numLines":175,"startLine":800,"totalLines":974}}}
