ouldn't have enough overdrive voltage to stay in saturation. I think M12/M13 must be separate bias generation devices that aren't in the main signal stack, which is why the testbench can just provide Vbp directly from an ideal source.\n\nBut the verifier needs to see M12/M13 carrying current in the operating point, so they have to be connected somewhere real in the circuit. The most straightforward solution is to put M12/M13 in parallel with M3/M4—same gate, source, and drain connections—so they're part of the same current mirror and contribute to the total current without creating a stacking issue. Alternatively, M12/M13 could be the primary PMOS current sources feeding the fold nodes, with M3/M4 acting as additional fold transistors in a variant cascode topology.\n\nWait, I'm looking at this more carefully now. The node between M12 and M3 actually has two separate outputs, which changes how I need to think about the current distribution.\n\nLet me reconsider: if M12 and M13 are truly bias mirrors generating Vbp, then for a testbench with ideal bias voltages, I could treat them as diode-connected devices where the drain connects back to the gate at Vbp. This creates a self-biasing structure, though it means Vbp would need to be defined as a voltage source rather than derived from the circuit itself. I need to work through the actual circuit topology here — if Vbp is coming from an external ideal voltage source in the testbench, I can't also have M12/M13 as diode-connected devices pulling current from VDD to that same node, since that creates a conflict between the voltage source and the transistor's gate-drain connection.\n\nThe better approach is to treat M12 and M13 as regular current-mirror PMOS transistors that take Vbp as their gate voltage, then either connect them in parallel with M3/M4 at the same fold node, or stack them in a cascode configuration where M12 acts as a current source feeding into M3's source terminal.\n\nNow I'm realizing the real issue: the