the same Vbn bias as M11, I can size M9 with a W/L ratio of 2 to match this requirement.\n\nWait, I'm checking the mirror ratio and realizing I've made an error—if M9 has W/L = 2 and M11 has W/L = 1, then M9 will carry twice the current of M11, which would be 1000nA. That's far too high. I actually need the mirror ratio to be 0.5 to get 250nA, so I need to adjust the W/L sizing accordingly. I see the issue now—the testbench uses ideal voltage sources for the bias rather than an actual current mirror, so each transistor's current depends only on its own W/L ratio and the fixed gate voltage, not on mirroring from a reference. With Vbn set directly, M9 (4/2) will draw twice the current of M11 (4/4) regardless of the intended ratio, which explains why I'm getting 1000nA instead of the target 250nA.\n\nTo fix this, I need to resize M9 and M10 to have a W/L ratio of 0.5 relative to M11, bringing their current down to the required 250nA.\n\nNow I'm working through the PMOS side—M3 and M4 need to carry specific currents determined by their W/L ratios since they all share the same bias voltage. Using KCL at the fold nodes, I can see that I_M1 should be half of I_M11 (250nA), and I_M7 needs to match I_M9 at 250nA to maintain the cascode balance.\n\nWith those currents set, the total supply current comes to 1µA, which is comfortably under the 2µA spec, though the program's 1.5µA suggests they used a different current distribution across the stages.\n\nNow for the transistor sizing: M9 and M10 need to pass 250nA when the tail current M11 is at 500nA, giving a ratio of 0.5. That means W9/L9 should be half of W11/L11. But the program shows W9=4µm and L9=2µm, which would actually give a ratio of 2 relative to M11—the opposite of what I calculated. Let me reconsider what mirror configuration they're using here.\n\nActually, I think the program may have intended M9 and M10 to operate independently at 250nA each, but with Vbn shared across the circuit, the sizing becomes inconsistent