{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Q96Com7SkZNz5WmJUBLMEH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait! Look at these results:\n- W=0.42u L=1u: At applied Vsg=0.877V, the actual Vth=0.920V, so Vov = 0.877 - 0.920 = -43mV (STILL NEGATIVE!)\n- W=0.84u L=1u: At Vsg=0.900V, Vth=0.949V, Vov = -49mV\n\n\n- W=0.42u L=2u: At Vsg=0.859V, Vth=0.906V, Vov = -47mV\n\nThe diode-connected measurement gave me Vth=0.727V, but that's clearly not the actual threshold voltage under these operating conditions—BSIM4 models Vth as bias-dependent, changing with Vds and Vbs, which explains why I'm seeing much higher values when I apply different gate-source voltages.\n\nThe diode-connected test had minimal Vds, while the saturation test has larger Vds, triggering significant DIBL effects that shift the threshold voltage up to around 0.92V. I was also operating in subthreshold during that initial measurement, where the reported Vth behaves differently than in strong inversion.\n\nSo the real Vth at my target operating point is 0.92V, not 0.73V—meaning I need Vsg = 1.07V to hit Vov=150mV, which puts Vbp at 0.73V. Let me run the test again with these corrected values.\n\nThe current at Vsg=0.877V is only 33nA, which is far too low for my 500nA target per branch. At this bias point the device is in weak inversion with negative Vov. I need to push Vsg higher or increase the device size. Earlier data showed that Vsg=1.15V with W=0.42u and L=4u gave 235nA at Vov=246mV, so I'll try Vsg around 1.1V with a shorter channel length to boost the current.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3960,"cache_read_input_tokens":196310,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3960},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"37d800