{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01JFsjGdxhZ72KhYimyEJyFY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The AC analysis works with .control block! But the results are terrible:\n- gain_peak = 6.75 dB → expected >60dB!\n- UGB = 30.8kHz (in range 30-150kHz ✓)\n- Phase at UGB = -1.1° → PM = -1.1 + 180 = 178.9° → WAY too high\n\nThe gain of only 6.75dB means the OTA isn't functioning properly as an amplifier. The 1MΩ stabilization resistors are loading the output and killing the gain!\n\n\nI can see what's happening now—the 1MΩ bias resistors are acting as a parallel load that's collapsing the output impedance from ~100MΩ down to ~1MΩ, which explains why the gain is only 6.75dB instead of the expected 60dB+. I need to switch to much higher resistance values for the AC test to avoid this loading effect.\n\nThe solution is to use a loop-breaking inductor technique instead—I'll connect the output back to the negative input through a 1GH inductor, which passes DC to set the operating point but presents very high impedance at AC frequencies, effectively opening the feedback loop during the AC analysis.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1010,"cache_read_input_tokens":300343,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1010},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"37d800be-0a8d-4fa4-9160-013da436175b","uuid":"671489eb-83da-41b4-9600-40154a374400"}
